<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="ch5-section-expanding-acceleration-subsection-j-hat" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Expanding the total derivative of <m>\hat{j}</m></title>

    <p>
        Again using the definition of the total derivative,
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-j-full" number="yes"> 
            \frac{D \hat{j}}{Dt}
            =
            \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial t}
            + u \, \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial x}
            + v \, \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial y}
            + w \, \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial z}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        Again, the first term on the right-hand side of <xref ref="eqn-total-derivative-j-full" text="type-global" /> is
    </p>
    
    <p>
        <md>
            \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial t} = \vec{0}
        </md>
    </p>
    
    <p>
        since,
        at a fixed location on Earth or in its atmosphere,
        the local orientation of a unit direction vector does not change with time.
        Specifically,
        <m>\hat{j}</m> always points to the local north. 
    </p>

    <p>
        Furthermore,
        <xref ref="ch5-local-cartesian-coordinates-sphericity" text="type-global" />
        reveals that
    </p>
        
    <p>
        <md>
            \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial z} = \vec{0}
        </md>
    </p>
    
    <p>
        Therefore, <xref ref="eqn-total-derivative-j-full" text="type-global" /> reduces to
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-j-reduced" number="yes"> 
            \frac{D \hat{j}}{Dt}
            =
            u \, \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial x}
            + v \, \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial y}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        To evaluate <m>\dfrac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial x}</m>,
        we again make a horizontal slice perpendicular to Earth's axis of rotation at latitude <m>\phi</m>
        to create a disk of radius <m>a \cos{\phi}</m>.
        As shown in <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-x-start" text="type-global" /> below,
        we then consider the difference in <m>\hat{j}</m>'s orientation
        when its anchoring point is placed at two nearby points on Earth's surface with latitude <m>\phi</m>
        and longitudes separated by angle <m>\delta \lambda</m> along arc <m>\delta x</m>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch5-spherical-j-x-start">
        <caption>
            North polar projection showing portions of unit direction vectors
            <m>\hat{j}_1 \, \sin{\phi}</m> and <m>\hat{j}_2 \, \sin{\phi}</m>
            placed on Earth's surface at two nearby points at the edge of the disk of radius <m>a \cos{\phi}</m>
            and separated by angle <m>\delta \lambda</m> and arc <m>\delta x</m>.
            The disk is bounded by circle of latitude <m>\phi</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ch5-spherical-j-x-start.png" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>
                Two portions of unit direction vectors at two nearby points
                on the edge of a circular disk viewed from above.
                The vectors point inward toward the center of the disk.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Before going further,
        note that <m>\hat{j} \, \sin{\phi}</m> rather than <m>\hat{j}</m> is shown in <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-x-start" text="type-global" />
        because <m>\hat{j} \, \sin{\phi}</m> is the projection of <m>\hat{j}</m> onto the disk,
        as shown in <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-x-breakdown" text="type-global" /> below.
        The remaining portion of <m>\hat{j}</m>,
        <m>\hat{j} \, \cos{\phi}</m>,
        does not change with <m>x</m>,
        as it always points vertically upward from the disk.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch5-spherical-j-x-breakdown">
        <caption>
            Equatorial projection showing the unit direction vectors <m>\hat{i}</m>, <m>\hat{j}</m>, and <m>\hat{k}</m>
            of the local Cartesian coordinate system fixed to Earth's surface at radius <m>a \cos{\phi}</m>
            perpendicular to Earth's axis of rotation,
            where <m>a</m> is Earth's mean radius and <m>\phi</m> is latitude.
            The portion of <m>\hat{j}</m> that points inward perpendicular to Earth's axis of rotation
            is given by <m>\hat{j} \, \sin{\phi}</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ch5-spherical-j-x-breakdown.png" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>
                A point on Earth's surface with the local Cartesian coordinate system
                as well as a vector projection pointing inward perpendicular to Earth's axis of rotation
                placed at that point.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Fixing the tails of <m>\hat{j}_1 \, \sin{\phi}</m> and <m>\hat{j}_2 \, \sin{\phi}</m> together in
        <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-x-zoom" text="type-global" /> below
        reveals that <m>\delta \lambda</m> is the angle swept out between them
        and <m>\vec{\delta j}</m> is the vector difference between them.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch5-spherical-j-x-zoom">
        <caption>
            Reproduction of <m>\hat{j}_1 \, \sin{\phi}</m> and <m>\hat{j}_2 \, \sin{\phi}</m>
            from <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-x-start" text="type-global" />.
            When the tails of the vectors are fixed together,
            they are separated by angle <m>\delta \lambda</m>
            and their vector difference is <m>\vec{\delta j}</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ch5-spherical-j-x-zoom.png" width="35%">
            <shortdescription>
                Two portions of unit direction vectors with their tails fixed together
                and the angle swept out between them and their vector difference annotated.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Reproducing <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-x-start" text="type-global" />
        with the tail of <m>\hat{j}_1 \, \sin{\phi}</m> moved to the tail of <m>\hat{j}_2 \, \sin{\phi}</m>
        and <m>\vec{\delta j}</m> additionally included
        in <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-x-end" text="type-global" /> below makes these relationships even clearer.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch5-spherical-j-x-end">
        <caption>
            Reproduction of <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-x-start" text="type-global" />
            with the tail of <m>\hat{j}_1 \, \sin{\phi}</m> moved to the tail of <m>\hat{j}_2 \, \sin{\phi}</m>.
            As shown in <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-x-zoom" text="type-global" />,
            <m>\hat{j}_1 \, \sin{\phi}</m> and <m>\hat{j}_2 \, \sin{\phi}</m> are separated by angle <m>\delta \lambda</m>
            and their vector difference is <m>\vec{\delta j}</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ch5-spherical-j-x-end.png" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>
                Two portions of unit direction vectors with their tails fixed together
                and the angle swept out between them and their vector difference annotated.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        We again can use the arc length formula to approximate <m>|\vec{\delta j}|</m>,
        and we can take advantage of the fact that,
        since <m>\hat{j}</m> is a unit direction vector,
        <m>|\hat{j}| = 1</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
        <md number="yes">
            |\vec{\delta j}|
            = |\hat{j_1}|(\sin{\phi}) \, \delta \lambda
            = |\hat{j_2}|(\sin{\phi}) \, \delta \lambda
            = |\hat{j}|(\sin{\phi}) \, \delta \lambda
            = (\sin{\phi}) \, \delta \lambda
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        And as noted in <xref ref="ch5-section-expanding-acceleration-subsection-i-hat" text="type-global" />,
        <m>\delta x = (a \cos{\phi}) \, \delta \lambda</m>.
        Therefore,
    </p>

    <p>
        <md number="yes">
            \frac{|\vec{\delta j}|}{\delta x}
            =
            \frac{(\sin{\phi}) \, \delta \lambda}{(a \cos{\phi}) \, \delta \lambda}
            =
            \frac{\tan{\phi}}{a}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        From <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-x-end" text="type-global" />,
        we can see that as <m>\delta \lambda \to 0</m>,
        <m>\delta x \to 0</m> and <m>\vec{\delta j}</m> points in the <m>-\hat{i}</m> direction.
        So
    </p>

    <p>
        <md number="yes">
            \lim_{\delta x \to 0}
            \frac{\vec{\delta j}}{\delta x}
            =
            \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial x}
            =
            -\frac{\tan{\phi}}{a} \, \hat{i}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        To evaluate <m>\dfrac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial y}</m>,
        we make a vertical slice through Earth's axis of rotation at longitude <m>\lambda</m>.
        As shown in <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-y-start" text="type-global" /> below,
        we then consider the change in <m>\hat{j}</m>'s orientation
        when its anchoring point is placed at two nearby points on Earth's surface with longitude <m>\lambda</m>
        and latitudes separated by angle <m>\delta \phi</m> along arc <m>\delta y</m>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch5-spherical-j-y-start">
        <caption>
            Equatorial projection showing unit direction vectors <m>\hat{j}_1</m> and <m>\hat{j}_2</m> placed on Earth's surface
            at two nearby points with longitude <m>\lambda</m>
            and separated by angle <m>\delta \phi</m> and arc <m>\delta y</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ch5-spherical-j-y-start.png" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>
                Two unit direction vectors at two nearby points
                on the edge of a circular disk viewed from the side.
                The vectors point tangent to the edge of the disk.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Fixing the tails of <m>\hat{j}_1</m> and <m>\hat{j}_2</m> together in
        <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-y-zoom" text="type-global" /> below
        reveals that <m>\delta \phi</m> is the angle swept out between them
        and <m>\vec{\delta j}</m> is the vector difference between them.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch5-spherical-j-y-zoom">
        <caption>
            Reproduction of <m>\hat{j}_1</m> and <m>\hat{j}_2</m> from <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-y-start" text="type-global" />.
            When the tails of the vectors are fixed together,
            they are separated by angle <m>\delta \phi</m> and their vector difference is <m>\vec{\delta j}</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ch5-spherical-j-y-zoom.png" width="30%">
            <shortdescription>
                Two unit direction vectors with their tails fixed together
                and the angle swept out between them and their vector difference annotated.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        Reproducing <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-y-start" text="type-global" />
        with the tail of <m>\hat{j}_1</m> moved to the tail of <m>\hat{j}_2</m> and <m>\vec{\delta j}</m> additionally included
        in <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-y-end" text="type-global" /> below makes these relationships even clearer.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch5-spherical-j-y-end">
        <caption>
            Reproduction of <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-y-start" text="type-global" />
            with the tail of <m>\hat{j}_1</m> moved to the tail of <m>\hat{j}_2</m>.
            As shown in <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-y-zoom" text="type-global" />,
            <m>\hat{j}_1</m> and <m>\hat{j}_2</m> are separated by angle <m>\delta \phi</m>
            and their vector difference is <m>\vec{\delta j}</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ch5-spherical-j-y-end.png" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>
                Two unit direction vectors with their tails fixed together
                and the angle swept out between them and their vector difference annotated.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        We again can use the arc length formula to express <m>\delta y</m> in terms of <m>\delta \phi</m>:
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-delta-y" number="yes">
            \delta y
            =
            a \, \delta \phi
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        Note that we presented this formula in <xref ref="ch2-section-local-cartesian-coordinates" text="type-global" />.
    </p>

    <p>
        Likewise,
        we again can use the arc length formula to approximate <m>|\vec{\delta j}|</m>,
        and we can take advantage of the fact that,
        since <m>\hat{j}</m> is a unit direction vector,
        <m>|\hat{j}| = 1</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
        <md number="yes">
            |\vec{\delta j}|
            = |\hat{j_1}| \, \delta \phi
            = |\hat{j_2}| \, \delta \phi
            = |\hat{j}|\, \delta \phi
            = \delta \phi
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        Therefore,
    </p>

    <p>
        <md number="yes">
            \frac{|\vec{\delta j}|}{\delta y}
            =
            \frac{\delta \phi}{a \, \delta \phi}
            = \frac{1}{a}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        From <xref ref="ch5-spherical-j-y-end" text="type-global" />,
        we can see that as <m>\delta \phi \to 0</m>,
        <m>\delta y \to 0</m> and <m>\vec{\delta j}</m> points in the <m>-\hat{k}</m> direction.
        So
    </p>

    <p>
        <md number="yes">
            \lim_{\delta y \to 0}
            \frac{\vec{\delta j}}{\delta y}
            =
            \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial y}
            =
            -\frac{1}{a} \hat{k}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        and <xref ref="eqn-total-derivative-j-reduced" text="type-global" /> becomes
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-total-derivative-j-final" number="yes">
            \frac{D \hat{j}}{Dt}
            =
            u \, \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial x}
            + v \, \frac{\partial \hat{j}}{\partial y}
            =
            -\frac{u \tan{\phi}}{a} \, \hat{i}
            -\frac{v}{a} \, \hat{k}
        </md>
    </p>

</subsection>